<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>CSS Test: SVG presentation attribute and angle argument with turn unit on rotate</title>
    <link rel="author" title="Rebecca Hauck" href="rhauck@adobe.com"/>
    <link rel="help" href="http://www.w3.org/TR/css3-transforms/#svg-transform"/>
    <link rel="help" href="http://www.w3.org/TR/css3-transforms/#svg-angle"/>
    <link rel="help" href="http://www.w3.org/TR/css3-transforms/#two-d-transform-functions"/>
    <link rel="match" href="reftest/svg-rotate-angle-45-ref.xht"/>
    <meta name="flags" content="svg" />
    <meta name="assert" content="The rotate transform function must support the unit 'turn' on angle arguments. The circle in the test should be rotated by 45 degrees clockwise."/>
    <style type="text/css">
    svg {
        width: 300px;
        height: 300px;
    }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <p>You should see a 80x80 square divided vertically down the middle where the left half is fuchsia and the right half is orange.</p>
    <svg>
        <defs>
            <!-- Fill with gradient to make visible the circle's position after the rotation -->
            <linearGradient id="grad" x1="0%" y1="100%" >
                <stop offset="50%" stop-color="fuchsia" />
                <stop offset="50%" stop-color="orange" />
            </linearGradient>
            <!-- Clip a square path to clip away any anti-aliasing issues -->
            <clipPath id="clip">
                <path d = "M 41 130 L 121 130 L 121 210 L 41 210 Z"/>
            </clipPath>
        </defs>
        <g clip-path="url(#clip)">
            <circle cx="175" cy="60" r="60" fill="url(#grad)" transform="rotate(0.125turn)" />
        </g>
    </svg>
</body>
</html>
